Introduction

In this workshop, we will go through a basic workflow for analyzing single-cell RNA-sequencing data using the Seurat package. We will start by exploring the Seurat object, which is the backbone for storing and analyzing data.

In this workshop, we will consider two scRNA-seq data sets generated from two platforms, 10x Chromium (v2) & 10x Chromium (v3). PBMCs were sequenced from two patients.

Understanding the Seurat Object

A Seurat object is a structured container used for storing and analyzing single-cell RNA-seq data. It provides a convenient framework for handling various types of data (raw counts, normalized data, metadata, dimensionality reductions, clustering results, etc.) all in one place.

  • Check this out from Ming Tang https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gBiPdlZYbnw

Key Features of the Seurat Object:

  1. Assays (@assays):
    • This slot contains different layers of the data, typically centered around gene expression. The most commonly used assay is RNA, which stores the gene expression data for cells.
    • It contains:
      • Raw counts (@counts): The unnormalized count matrix (gene x cell).
      • Normalized data (@data): Log-normalized gene expression values.
      • Scaled data (@scale.data): Z-score normalized expression values for downstream dimensionality reduction.
  2. Metadata (@meta.data):
    • Metadata holds cell-specific information such as cell quality control metrics, cluster identity, and other annotations. This information can be used for visualization and further analysis.
    • For example, common metadata fields include:
      • nFeature_RNA: Number of genes detected per cell.
      • nCount_RNA: Total UMI (unique molecular identifier) counts per cell.
      • percent.mito: Percentage of reads mapping to mitochondrial genes (often used as a quality control metric).
  3. Dimensional Reductions (@reductions):
    • Stores the results of dimensionality reduction techniques like PCA, UMAP, or t-SNE. These are often used for visualizing the data in 2D or 3D spaces and for clustering cells based on gene expression similarities.
  4. Cell Identities (@active.ident):
    • This stores the identity class of each cell (e.g., clusters, cell types). It is crucial for grouping cells based on clustering or other predefined labels.

Exploring the Count Matrix

The count matrix is a core part of the Seurat object, and it contains the raw gene expression data from the single-cell RNA sequencing experiment. It is a matrix where: - Rows represent genes. - Columns represent cells. - Each entry in the matrix corresponds to the number of transcripts (or unique molecular identifiers) detected for a particular gene in a particular cell.

Viewing the Raw Count Matrix

To view the raw count matrix for any Seurat object, you can access it through the @assays$RNA@counts slot.

# View the raw count matrix for 10x Chromium v2
pbmc_10x_v2@assays$RNA
## Assay data with 33694 features for 3362 cells
## First 10 features:
##  TSPAN6, TNMD, DPM1, SCYL3, C1orf112, FGR, CFH, FUCA2, GCLC, NFYA
#raw_counts_v2 <- pbmc_10x_v2@assays$RNA@counts
#dim(raw_counts_v2)  # Check dimensions of the matrix (genes x cells)

# View the raw count matrix for 10x Chromium v3
raw_counts_v3 <- pbmc_10x_v3@assays$RNA@counts
dim(raw_counts_v3)
## [1] 33694  3222

Count Matrix in a Dense Format

By default, the count matrix in Seurat is stored as a sparse matrix to save memory, as scRNA-seq data contains many zeros (representing genes that are not expressed in a given cell). However, you can convert this sparse matrix into a dense matrix if you want to view the real counts.

# Convert the sparse matrix to a dense matrix
dense_counts_v2 <- as.matrix(pbmc_10x_v2@assays$RNA@counts)
dense_counts_v3 <- as.matrix(pbmc_10x_v3@assays$RNA@counts)

# View a portion of the dense matrix (first 5 genes and first 5 cells)

Note: Dense matrices can consume significantly more memory, so it’s recommended to work with sparse matrices when possible, especially with large datasets.

Summary

  • The Seurat object is a powerful structure that encapsulates raw data, metadata, results from dimensionality reductions, and cluster assignments.
  • The count matrix holds raw gene expression data in a sparse matrix format by default. You can view or manipulate this matrix for specific analyses, and if necessary, convert it to a dense matrix format.

Quality Control (QC) Step

Step 1: Calculate common QC metrics such as:

- Number of features (genes) detected per cell (nFeature_RNA)

- Total UMI counts per cell (nCount_RNA)

- Percentage of mitochondrial genes per cell (percent.mito)

#### Calculate the percentage of mitochondrial genes
pbmc_10x_v3[["percent.mito"]] <- PercentageFeatureSet(pbmc_10x_v3, pattern = "^MT-")
pbmc_10x_v3$percent.mito <- as.numeric(pbmc_10x_v3$percent.mito)

#### Visualize the QC metrics with violin plots
VlnPlot(pbmc_10x_v3, features = c("nFeature_RNA", "nCount_RNA", "percent.mito"), ncol = 3)

#### Step 2: Examine relationships between QC metrics using scatter plots
FeatureScatter(pbmc_10x_v3, feature1 = "nCount_RNA", feature2 = "percent.mito") +
  FeatureScatter(pbmc_10x_v3, feature1 = "nCount_RNA", feature2 = "nFeature_RNA")

class(pbmc_10x_v3$percent.mito)
## [1] "numeric"
class(pbmc_10x_v3$nFeature_RNA)
## [1] "integer"
class(pbmc_10x_v3$nCount_RNA)
## [1] "numeric"

Filtering Low-Quality Cells

## Step 3: Filter out low-quality cells based on the following thresholds:
# - Minimum number of genes: 100
# - Maximum number of genes: 2500
# - Maximum percentage of mitochondrial genes: 5%
pbmc_10x_v3
## An object of class Seurat 
## 33694 features across 3222 samples within 1 assay 
## Active assay: RNA (33694 features, 0 variable features)
##  2 layers present: counts, data
# Define filtering thresholds
min_features <- 200   # Minimum number of genes per cell
max_features <- 2500  # Maximum number of genes per cell
max_mito <- 15         # Maximum percent of mitochondrial genes

# Filter out poor-quality cells
pbmc_10x_v3 <- subset(pbmc_10x_v3, subset = nFeature_RNA > min_features & nFeature_RNA < max_features & percent.mito < max_mito)

# Step 4: Visualize the filtered dataset to confirm QC filtering worked
VlnPlot(pbmc_10x_v3, features = c("nFeature_RNA", "nCount_RNA", "percent.mito"), ncol = 3)

#pbmc_10x_v3@meta.data

Data Normalization in Seurat

What is Normalization?

Normalization is a critical step in single-cell RNA-seq analysis. It accounts for differences in sequencing depth between cells, allowing for more accurate comparison of gene expression levels. Each cell may have a different number of detected transcripts, either due to biological variation or technical differences, and normalization ensures that the data is comparable across cells.

Normalization in Seurat

In Seurat, normalization is typically performed using the log-normalization method, where the raw counts are scaled by the total number of counts per cell, multiplied by a scaling factor (typically 10,000), and then log-transformed.

The Steps:

  1. Scale the raw counts: Each gene expression value is divided by the total number of UMI counts for that cell, ensuring that differences in library size (sequencing depth) between cells are taken into account.
  2. Multiply by a scaling factor: The scaled values are multiplied by a factor (default is 10,000) to avoid very small numbers after normalization.
  3. Log-transform: Logarithmic transformation is applied to stabilize the variance and reduce the effect of high-abundance genes, making the data more suitable for downstream analysis like clustering or dimensionality reduction.

This process ensures that cells with different total read counts can still be compared.

A fictional table from ChatGPT 

# Perform normalization

pbmc_10x_v3 <- NormalizeData(pbmc_10x_v3, normalization.method = "LogNormalize", scale.factor = 10000)

Feature Selection in Seurat

What is Feature Selection?

Feature selection is a crucial step in the analysis of single-cell RNA-seq data. It involves identifying the most variable genes across cells, which are more likely to carry biologically relevant information for downstream analyses such as clustering or trajectory inference.

In single-cell RNA-seq, many genes are either not expressed or have very low variation across cells. Including all genes can introduce noise and reduce the sensitivity of downstream analysis. Therefore, we focus on highly variable genes for dimensionality reduction and clustering.

Highly Variable Genes (HVGs)

Seurat uses a method to calculate the variance-to-mean ratio (VMR) of each gene’s expression across cells. These values are then used to identify highly variable genes (HVGs).

Alt Variance Formula

Feature Selection in Seurat

Seurat offers a function, FindVariableFeatures(), that automatically identifies the highly variable features (genes) for downstream analysis.

# Identify highly variable features
pbmc_10x_v3 <- FindVariableFeatures(pbmc_10x_v3, selection.method = "vst", nfeatures = 2000)

# View the top 10 variable features
top10 <- head(VariableFeatures(pbmc_10x_v3), 10)
top10
##  [1] "S100A9" "LYZ"    "S100A8" "IGKC"   "IGLC2"  "PPBP"   "NRGN"   "IGLC3" 
##  [9] "GNLY"   "PF4"

Scaling the Data in Seurat

What is Scaling?

Scaling is an important step in single-cell RNA-seq analysis, where we standardize the expression values across genes and cells. This is crucial because genes may have different ranges of expression levels, and we want to make sure that highly expressed genes don’t dominate the downstream analysis.

In Seurat, scaling means subtracting the mean of each gene’s expression and dividing by the standard deviation (Z-score normalization). This standardizes the expression levels so that all genes have a mean of 0 and a variance of 1 across the dataset.

Important Note:

  • By default, Seurat only scales the highly variable genes identified in the previous step (feature selection).
  • If you’re planning to perform regression-based corrections (e.g., for mitochondrial genes or cell cycle effects), it’s best to apply them during this scaling step.

Scaling the Data in Seurat

all.genes <- rownames(pbmc_10x_v3)
pbmc_10x_v3 <- ScaleData(pbmc_10x_v3, features = all.genes)
## Centering and scaling data matrix

2. Perform Linear Dimensional Reduction

Linear Dimensional Reduction: PCA

What is Linear Dimensional Reduction?

Linear dimensional reduction techniques, such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA), are used to reduce the complexity of large single-cell RNA-seq datasets by projecting the data into fewer dimensions. PCA identifies the axes (principal components) that capture the most variance in the dataset, allowing us to simplify the dataset while retaining its most informative aspects.

Why PCA?

  • PCA reduces noise by focusing on the most informative components, which speeds up the clustering process and other downstream analyses.
  • We can identify the principal components (PCs) that explain the most variance, helping to reduce dimensionality before clustering.

Important Note:

  • PCA assumes that the data is linearly separable and works best when the signal in the data is structured. However, for capturing non-linear patterns, Seurat later uses techniques like UMAP or t-SNE.

I strongly recommend you guys to watch the following video; StatQuest: Principal Component Analysis (PCA), Step-by-Step

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FgakZw6K1QQ

Running PCA in Seurat

# Perform PCA on the scaled data
pbmc_10x_v3 <- RunPCA(pbmc_10x_v3, features = VariableFeatures(object = pbmc_10x_v3))

Clustering the Cells

What is Clustering?

Clustering is the process of grouping cells with similar gene expression profiles. In single-cell RNA-seq data, clustering helps to identify distinct cell types or states. Seurat uses a graph-based clustering method, which is particularly effective for high-dimensional scRNA-seq data.

Graph-Based Clustering in Seurat

Seurat’s clustering algorithm follows these steps: 1. Find Neighbors: Constructs a nearest neighbor graph of the cells based on their PCA scores. 2. Find Clusters: Partitions the graph into communities (clusters) using the Louvain algorithm.

Clustering Cells in Seurat

# Construct the KNN graph
pbmc_10x_v3 <- FindNeighbors(pbmc_10x_v3, dims = 1:10)
## Computing nearest neighbor graph
## Computing SNN
# Perform clustering
pbmc_10x_v3 <- FindClusters(pbmc_10x_v3, resolution = 0.5)

## Number of edges: 76465

Non-Linear Dimensional Reduction: UMAP and t-SNE

UMAP (Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection)

UMAP is a non-linear dimensional reduction technique that preserves local and global structures.

Perform UMAP using the first 30 principal components
pbmc_10x_v3 <- RunUMAP(pbmc_10x_v3, dims = 1:30)

##### Visualize the clusters in UMAP space

DimPlot(pbmc_10x_v3, reduction = "umap", label = TRUE)

—- Detailed Explanation for UMAP —-

UMAP is a faster method than t-SNE and is often preferred for visualizing large single-cell RNA-seq datasets.
UMAP preserves both local and global structures in the data, allowing for better separation of clusters.
It’s commonly used in scRNA-seq to create a 2D or 3D map of cells, based on their gene expression profiles.

————————————————————————

t-SNE (t-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding)

t-SNE is a non-linear dimensional reduction technique that is commonly used in single-cell RNA-seq visualization.
##### Perform t-SNE using the first 10 principal components

pbmc_10x_v3 <- RunTSNE(pbmc_10x_v3, dims = 1:10)

#### Visualize the clusters in t-SNE space

DimPlot(pbmc_10x_v3, reduction = "tsne", label = TRUE)

—- Detailed Explanation for t-SNE —-

t-SNE is slower than UMAP and focuses more on preserving local structures (neighborhoods).
It can sometimes distort global relationships (i.e., distances between clusters) but is still widely used in scRNA-seq.

t-SNE is known to give slightly different results each time due to its stochastic nature, unlike UMAP which is more consistent.

————————————————————————

Additional Notes:

- Both UMAP and t-SNE work on the top principal components (PCs) from PCA. Usually, the first 10-30 PCs are used,
depending on the dataset.
This is set using the dims argument (as shown above, dims = 1:10).
- UMAP is often preferred for larger datasets due to its speed and ability to preserve both local and global structure.
- If you observe clusters that are not well separated, try adjusting the number of PCs or using a different resolution
during the clustering process.

Finding Cluster Biomarkers (Differentially Expressed Features)

Explanation:
Finding differentially expressed features (markers) between clusters helps identify genes
that define distinct cell types or states within the dataset. Seurat’s FindMarkers() function
identifies genes that are significantly upregulated in one cluster compared to all others.
Find markers for cluster 1 compared to all other clusters
cluster1_markers <- FindMarkers(pbmc_10x_v3, ident.1 = 1, min.pct = 0.25)

# Explanation:
# - `ident.1 = 1`: Specifies that we are finding markers for cluster 1.
# - `min.pct = 0.25`: The minimum fraction of cells in the cluster that must express the gene
#   for it to be considered a marker (here, 25% of cells).
# - This returns a data frame with markers, their fold changes, and statistical significance.

# View the top 5 markers for cluster 1
head(cluster1_markers, n = 5)
##                 p_val avg_log2FC pct.1 pct.2     p_val_adj
## IL7R    1.437281e-156  2.1598498 0.949 0.305 4.842774e-152
## LTB     2.765103e-142  2.0884491 0.957 0.371 9.316738e-138
## TPT1    4.342265e-106  0.6119134 1.000 0.993 1.463083e-101
## ZFP36L2 6.778540e-100  1.3329570 0.995 0.844  2.283961e-95
## LDHB     2.593815e-92  1.3527786 0.957 0.646  8.739599e-88
# Explanation:
# The head() function shows the top 5 differentially expressed genes (markers) for cluster 1.
# Each row represents a gene, and the columns include p-values, fold changes, and other statistics.

Visualizing Markers for Specific Clusters

Explanation:
Once markers are identified, you can visualize their expression across clusters using
Seurat’s plotting functions, such as VlnPlot() for violin plots and FeaturePlot() for spatial gene plots.
# Example: Visualize the expression of CD3D and CD14 (common immune cell markers)
# Using Violin Plot (VlnPlot)
VlnPlot(pbmc_10x_v3, features = c("CD3D", "CD14","SPARC"), pt.size = 0.1)

# Explanation:
# - `features = c("CD3D", "CD14")`: Specifies the genes to visualize (e.g., CD3D, a T-cell marker, and CD14, a monocyte marker).
# - `pt.size = 0.1`: Controls the size of individual points on the plot.

# Example: Visualize gene expression spatially across the UMAP plot using FeaturePlot
#raw_counts_v2FeaturePlot(pbmc_10x_v3, features = c("CD3D", "CD14"))

# Explanation:
# - `FeaturePlot()` shows where specific genes are expressed across the UMAP (or t-SNE) plot.
#   In this example, we visualize the expression of CD3D and CD14 across the clusters.
pbmc.markers %>%
    group_by(cluster) %>%
    dplyr::filter(avg_log2FC > 1) %>%
    slice_head(n = 5) %>%
    ungroup() -> top10
DoHeatmap(pbmc_10x_v3, features = top10$gene)
